RHULANI Mokwena said his final goodbyes to the Chippa United family on Tuesday as his short spell at the club officially came to an end. This after the former Orlando Pirates interim coach's contract was not renewed by the Chilli Boys, as previously reported by SunSport. READ: RHULANI FACES THE BOOT Mokwena, who joined the Port Elizabeth outfit in an unusual loan deal until the end of the season, will not see out the remainder of the current campaign. In a heartfelt message posted on his social media pages, Mokwena thanked everyone at the club for their support during his short stint. “After six months at the helm, It's with overwhelming emotion that I officially announce that I have successfully served my loan contract as coach of Chippa United and close a short yet extremely beneficial period of my coaching career," Mokwena wrote. "As we complete our contact, we depart with respect, dignity and appreciation knowing that we leave the club better than we found it."I want to thank the chairman, his family and the management for the opportunity and support. The technical team for their support, patience, hard work and sacrifice. We spent lockdown together in Port Elizabeth, you risked your safety and sacrificed time away from your families just so you could put in the work which went beyond the ordinary 24 hours. You guys are incredible and it was a pleasure working with you. "Thank you to the people of Port Elizabeth and the Chilli Boys supporters for the warm reception and your hospitality. You've got a great club that's got a lot more potential than you can imagine. Last but not least, my biggest thank you goes to the Chippa United players. Contrary to what the log says, there is incredible talent and I look forward to seeing what the future holds for each and every single one of you. Thank you for your hard work, humility and trust."Wishing the club and all its people all the best in its future endeavours.”